TI  - Preparation and characterization of La/g-C3N4/TiO2 quantum dots and their detection of FLE-Induced degradation: A bifunctional study and its correlation with traditional Chinese medicine antitumor therapy applications
T2  - JOURNAL OF THE INDIAN CHEMICAL SOCIETY
LA  - English
KW  - FLE
KW  - Phosphorescent probe
KW  - Quantum dots
KW  - Photocatalysis
KW  - Jiawei huai hua powder
KW  - Intestinal tumor therapy
KW  - PHOTOCATALYTIC ACTIVITY
KW  - NANOCOMPOSITES
KW  - FABRICATION
KW  - DRIVEN
AB  - Fleroxacin (FLE), a third-generation fluoroquinolone, is widely used in infection prevention for intestinal tumor patients but its residues in the intestinal microenvironment disrupt the efficacy of the classic traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) regimen-Jiawei Huaihua Powder (JHP) combined with Purgation Method (PM)-by disturbing gut microbiota and interacting with JHP active components. To address this bottleneck for the mechanism study of JHP-PM in intestinal tumor treatment, we prepared La/g-C3N4 co-doped TiO2 (GLT) quantum dots via a twostep sol-gel method using tetrabutyl titanate as precursor and melamine as C/N source. For detection, FLE quenched GLT's phosphorescence, enabling a rapid FLE determination method. Under optimal conditions, the phosphorescent quenching signal (P0/P) showed a good linear relationship with FLE concentration in the range of 0.5-50 mu g/mL (correlation coefficient r = 0.997), with a relative standard deviation (RSD) of 3.8% and a detection limit of 0.11 mu g/mL. Selectivity tests with JHP active components (rutin, quercetin, baicalin) confirmed GLT's reliability in JHP-PM-related scenarios. For photocatalysis, 20 mg/L FLE aqueous solution was used as the target pollutant. GLT-mediated FLE degradation followed the pseudo-first-order kinetic model (rate constant k = 0.00439 min-1, R2 = 0.9907), with activity significantly higher than that of pure TiO2 and La/TiO2. This enhancement was attributed to La-induced TiO2 grain refinement (verified by XRD) and g-C3N4-facilitated photogenerated charge separation (confirmed by XPS and fluorescence lifetime analysis). GLT was stable under simulated intestinal pH (6.0-7.5), retaining 90% of its phosphorescent and photocatalytic activity. In summary, this dual-functional GLT system not only provides a novel approach for FLE pollution control but also offers technical support for the in-depth mechanism study of JHP-PM in intestinal tumor treatment, bridging nano-material research and TCM-based cancer therapy.
